Monotonicity

Monotonicity constrains in ecological modelling

# read records
presences <- read.csv("Data/dataBases/Paramuricea_clavata.csv", sep = ";")
presences <- presences[, c("Lon", "Lat")]

# load layers of ocean temperatures, oxygen and productivity
envCond <- load_layers(c("BO2_tempmin_bdmean", "BO2_tempmax_bdmean", "BO2_dissoxmean_bdmean", 
    "BO2_ppmean_bdmean"))

# crop layers to the European extent
europeanExtent <- extent(-15, 40, 25, 50)
envCond <- crop(envCond, europeanExtent)

# generate pseudo absences
absences <- pseudoAbsences(envCond, presences, n = 10000)
S8 // Data-driven hyperparameter and variable selection

# extract environmental values and make a data.frame with PA information
modelData <- prepareModelData(presences, absences, envCond)

# fit a BRT model to the dataset
model <- train("BRT", modelData, folds = NULL)

plotResponse(model, var = "BO2_tempmin_bdmean", color = "Black")

S8 // Data-driven hyperparameter and variable selection

# prepare a dataset of monotonicity constrains
monotonicity <- data.frame(BO2_tempmin_bdmean = 1, BO2_tempmax_bdmean = -1, BO2_dissoxmean_bdmean = 1, 
    BO2_ppmean_bdmean = 1)

# fit a BRT model to the dataset with monotonicity constrains
model <- train("BRT", modelData, folds = NULL)

# inspect the effect of one variable
plotResponse(model, var = "BO2_tempmin_bdmean", color = "Black")

Hyperparameter selection

Data-driven hyperparameter selection

Proper hyperparameter selection allows to develop model with higher potential for transferability.

# generate background information
background <- backgroundInformation(envCond, n = 10000)

# extract environmental values and make a data.frame with PA information
modelData <- prepareModelData(presences, background, envCond)

# fit a Maxent model to the dataset with threshold feature and no regularization
model <- train("Maxnet", modelData, fc = "t", folds = NULL)
S8 // Data-driven hyperparameter and variable selection

# inspect the effect of one variable
plotResponse(model, var = "BO2_dissoxmean_bdmean", type = "logistic", color = "Black")

S8 // Data-driven hyperparameter and variable selection

# fit a Maxent model with threshold feature and different regularization steps ( multiplier)
model <- train("Maxnet", modelData, reg = 1, fc = "t", folds = NULL)

# inspect the effect of one variable
plotResponse(model, var = "BO2_dissoxmean_bdmean", type = "logistic", color = "Black")

S8 // Data-driven hyperparameter and variable selection

# fit a Maxent model with threshold feature and different regularization steps ( multiplier)
model <- train("Maxnet", modelData, reg = 5, fc = "t", folds = NULL)

# inspect the effect of one variable
plotResponse(model, var = "BO2_dissoxmean_bdmean", type = "logistic", color = "Black")

S8 // Data-driven hyperparameter and variable selection

# fit a Maxent model with threshold feature and different regularization steps ( multiplier)
model <- train("Maxnet", modelData, reg = 25, fc = "t", folds = NULL)

# inspect the effect of one variable
plotResponse(model, var = "BO2_dissoxmean_bdmean", type = "logistic", color = "Black")

S8 // Data-driven hyperparameter and variable selection

# train a model with threshold feature
folds <- get.block(presences, background)
model <- train("Maxnet", modelData, folds = folds, fc = "tp")

# given a set of possible hyperparameter values (regularization)
h <- list(reg = seq(1, 10, 1))

# train models with all the possible combinations of hyperparameters
exp1 <- gridSearch(model, hypers = h, metric = "auc")
S8 // Data-driven hyperparameter and variable selection

plot(exp1)

head(exp1@results)
##   fc reg train_AUC  test_AUC   diff_AUC
## 1 tp   1 0.9748230 0.9569015 0.01792145
## 2 tp   2 0.9737703 0.9579117 0.01585864
## 3 tp   3 0.9730704 0.9570682 0.01600212
## 4 tp   4 0.9719004 0.9575696 0.01433074
## 5 tp   5 0.9702842 0.9575333 0.01275090
## 6 tp   6 0.9688070 0.9572604 0.01154668
S8 // Data-driven hyperparameter and variable selection

# get the best hyperparameter value and fit a model to the dataset
which.max(exp1@results$test_AUC)
## [1] 2
model <- train("Maxnet", modelData, folds = folds, fc = "tp", reg = 2)
plotResponse(model, var = "BO2_dissoxmean_bdmean", type = "logistic", color = "Black")

Variable selection

Data-driven variable selection

In cases which a model has some environmental variables ranked with very low contribution and one may want to remove them in order to reduce the complexity of the model.

# determine relative variable contribution and performance as AUC
viModel <- varImp(model, permut = 5)
plotVarImp(viModel)

S8 // Data-driven hyperparameter and variable selection

getAUC(model, test = TRUE)
## [1] 0.9579117
# reduce model complexity by dropping variable at a time and remove all variables that have a
# permutation importance lower than 5%.
reducedModel <- reduceVar(model, th = 5, metric = "auc", permut = 5)

# determine relative variable contribution and performance as AUC of the reduced model
viModel <- varImp(reducedModel, permut = 5)
S8 // Data-driven hyperparameter and variable selection

plotVarImp(viModel)

getAUC(model, test = TRUE)
## [1] 0.9579117
getAUC(reducedModel, test = TRUE)
## [1] 0.9550242
